 United Kingdom","Bury Saint Edmunds, West Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Saint John the Baptist Church, Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dising","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably an altered form of <b>Leising</b>, a habitational name from a place so named in Bavaria."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":13,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705202,"age":22,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705205,"age":33,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705206,"age":35,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705207,"age":49,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705208,"age":51,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Christopher Dising was born in 1536, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He married Mariam Spooner about 1560. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1590, in Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54, and was buried in Denham, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1536–1590":"1536–1590","1540–Female":"1540–Surnud","1561–